{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"137"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/137"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.47,0.07,0.16,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109749"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/137"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92148"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"2100"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109749"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to the pre-operative assessment clinic for planned left hip replacement surgery in two weeks\u0027 time. She has severe osteoarthritis of her left hip causing significant mobility limitation, and she walks with the aid of a stick. Her medical history includes percutaneous coronary intervention with two drug-eluting stents to the left main coronary artery four months ago for unstable angina, hypertension, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include aspirin, clopidogrel, carvedilol, metformin, and simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with pulse rate 84/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Examination of her left hip reveals reduced range of movement with pain on internal rotation. Cardiovascular examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan regarding her antiplatelet therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease clopidogrel and proceed with surgery","Delay surgery for at least two months","Cease aspirin and proceed with surgery","Cease both antiplatelet agents and proceed with surgery","Proceed with surgery on current medications"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has high ischaemic risk features due to her left main coronary artery disease, treated with drug-eluting stents four months ago. Left main disease carries one of the highest risks for stent thrombosis if dual antiplatelet therapy is discontinued prematurely. Current guidelines recommend six to 12 months of dual antiplatelet therapy for patients with acute coronary syndrome who have high ischaemic risk and low bleeding risk. Hence, this patient requires at least six months of dual antiplatelet therapy before elective surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelay surgery for at least two months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option as this would allow the patient to complete at least six months of dual antiplatelet therapy, significantly reducing her risk of stent thrombosis while still allowing her to have the necessary hip replacement surgery in a timely manner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease clopidogrel and proceed with surgery\u003C/strong\u003E would leave the patient on aspirin monotherapy only four months after stenting of the left main coronary artery, which carries an unacceptably high risk of stent thrombosis and major adverse cardiac events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease aspirin and proceed with surgery\u003C/strong\u003E would similarly leave the patient on clopidogrel monotherapy, which is insufficient protection against stent thrombosis at this early stage after percutaneous coronary intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECease both antiplatelet agents and proceed with surgery\u003C/strong\u003E would expose the patient to an extremely high risk of stent thrombosis, which could be catastrophic given the left main coronary artery location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed with surgery on current medications\u003C/strong\u003E would carry a significantly increased risk of perioperative bleeding during major orthopaedic surgery, which typically requires neuraxial anaesthesia and has substantial blood loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe decision should be made in consultation with the patient\u0027s cardiologist and the surgical team. For emergency surgery, the risk-benefit ratio would be different, but for elective procedures like hip replacement, it is prudent to wait until the minimum recommended duration of dual antiplatelet therapy has been completed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The standard duration of dual antiplatelet therapy after percutaneous coronary intervention with drug-eluting stents for acute coronary syndrome is six to 12 months for patients with high ischaemic risk and low bleeding risk.","Patients with high ischaemic risk features such as left main coronary artery disease require at least six months of dual antiplatelet therapy before elective surgery.","Premature discontinuation of dual antiplatelet therapy increases the risk of stent thrombosis and major adverse cardiac events."],"references":["Brieger D, Cullen L, Briffa T, Zaman S, Scott I, Papendick C, Bardsley K, Baumann A, Bennett AS, Clark RA, Edelman JJ, Inglis SC, Kuhn L, Livori A, Redfern J, Schneider H, Stewart J, Thomas L, Wing-Lun E, Zhang L, Ho E, Matthews S; other members of the Heart Foundation Working Group. Electronic address: clinicalevidence@heartfoundation.org.au. National Heart Foundation of Australia \u0026 Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Comprehensive Australian Clinical Guideline for Diagnosing and Managing Acute Coronary Syndromes 2025. Heart Lung Circ. 2025 Apr;34(4):309-397. doi: 10.1016/j.hlc.2025.02.102. PMID: 40180468. Available from: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/for-professionals/acs-guideline?tab=0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92148"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"137"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92148"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T21:30:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T21:31:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"137"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109749"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"